Python Syntax Basics ‚Äî Modules

Modules let you break your code into separate files so everything isn‚Äôt stuffed into one giant script.
They help organize logic, improve readability, and allow you to reuse code across multiple automation projects.

Think of modules as ‚Äúcontainers of functions and variables‚Äù you can plug into any script.

üì¶ 1. What Is a Module?

A module is simply a Python file (.py) that contains:

Variables

Functions

Classes

Logic you want to reuse

Example:
A file named math_utils.py is a module called math_utils.

üì• 2. Importing a Module
Basic import
import math

print(math.sqrt(25))

Importing specific things
from math import sqrt

print(sqrt(25))

Importing with an alias
import datetime as dt

print(dt.datetime.now())


Super common practice for large modules.

üìÅ 3. Creating Your Own Module
Step 1 ‚Äî create a file

math_utils.py

def add(a, b):
    return a + b

def subtract(a, b):
    return a - b

Step 2 ‚Äî import it in another file

main.py

import math_utils

print(math_utils.add(10, 5))

üß© 4. Using from with Custom Modules
from math_utils import add

print(add(3, 2))

üìÇ 5. Packages (Folders of Modules)

A package is a folder that contains multiple modules.

Folder structure:
project/
    utilities/
        __init__.py
        math_utils.py
        text_utils.py
    main.py


__init__.py tells Python ‚Äúthis folder is a package.‚Äù

Importing from a package:
from utilities.math_utils import add

üîß 6. Built-in Modules You‚Äôll Use Constantly for Automation
File system modules
import os
from pathlib import Path
import shutil

Data modules
import json
import csv

Time & scheduling
import time
import datetime

Automation-related
import requests      # APIs
import subprocess    # run shell commands

üöÄ 7. Installing External Modules (Packages)

You‚Äôll use pip to install libraries that aren‚Äôt built in.

pip install requests


Then:

import requests

üîí 8. Virtual Environments (Best Practice)

Keep dependencies clean per project.

python -m venv venv
.\venv\Scripts\activate   # Windows
source venv/bin/activate  # Mac/Linux


Install packages inside it:

pip install -r requirements.txt

üìÑ 9. requirements.txt

This file lists your project‚Äôs dependencies.

Create it:

pip freeze > requirements.txt


Install it:

pip install -r requirements.txt


This is essential for automation scripts that run in cloud environments (Lambda, cron servers, CI/CD, etc.)

üß™ 10. Module Execution (if __name__ == "__main__":)

Python runs this block ONLY when the file is executed directly, not when imported.

def run():
    print("Running script")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    run()


Useful for separating ‚Äúscript mode‚Äù from ‚Äúimport mode.‚Äù

‚öôÔ∏è Real Automation Examples
Import a helper to clean text
from utils.text import clean_text

text = clean_text("   HELLO WORLD   ")

Use a module to handle API requests

api_utils.py

import requests

def get_json(url):
    return requests.get(url).json()


main.py

from api_utils import get_json

data = get_json("https://api.example.com")

Use modules to organize file tasks

file_ops.py

from pathlib import Path

def list_csv(folder):
    return list(Path(folder).glob("*.csv"))

üìù Quick Reference
import module
from module import name
from module import name as alias
import module as alias

# custom modules
def function(): ...
import my_module

# packages (folders)
project/
    package/
        __init__.py
        utils.py
